He's a very important man.

247
00:21:47,400 --> 00:21:49,200
Just give him two minutes of your time.

248
00:21:49,300 --> 00:21:52,700
Since when did time cost money? Just sit down and listen.

249
00:21:52,800 --> 00:21:55,000
Please. Sir?

250
00:21:58,700 --> 00:22:00,800
For each thousand you invest, I will repay you with...

251
00:22:00,800 --> 00:22:03,000
Two hundred. 200 kilos of enamelware a month,

252
00:22:03,100 --> 00:22:05,000
to begin in July and to continue for one year.

253
00:22:05,100 --> 00:22:08,900
After which time, we're even. That's it. It's very simple.

254
00:22:08,900 --> 00:22:11,900
Not good enough. It's not good enough.

255
00:22:11,900 --> 00:22:14,200
Not good enough?

256
00:22:14,300 --> 00:22:18,400
Look where you're living. Look where you've been put. ''Not good enough.''

257
00:22:18,500 --> 00:22:21,000
A couple of months ago you'd be right, not anymore.

258
00:22:21,100 --> 00:22:24,200
Money's still money.

259
00:22:25,800 --> 00:22:28,100
No, it is not.

260
00:22:28,100 --> 00:22:30,200
That's why we're here.

261
00:22:30,300 --> 00:22:32,300
Trade goods-- that's the only currency...

262
00:22:32,300 --> 00:22:34,300
that'll be worth anything in the ghetto.

263
00:22:34,300 --> 00:22:37,700
Things have changed, my friend.

264
00:22:38,500 --> 00:22:40,900
Did I call this meeting?

265
00:22:41,000 --> 00:22:43,400
You told Mr. Stern you wanted to speak to me.

266
00:22:43,500 --> 00:22:46,100
I'm here. I've made you a fair offer.

267
00:22:46,100 --> 00:22:50,100
Fair would be a percentage in the company.

268
00:22:50,200 --> 00:22:53,400
Forget the whole thing.

269
00:22:53,500 --> 00:22:55,800
Get out.

270
00:23:00,000 --> 00:23:03,100
How do we know that you will do what you say?

271
00:23:03,100 --> 00:23:05,100
Because I said I would.

272
00:23:05,100 --> 00:23:07,400
You want a contract? To be upheld by what court?

273
00:23:07,400 --> 00:23:10,400
I said what I'll do. That's our contract.

274
00:23:13,800 --> 00:23:16,000
...mielismy racje.

275
00:23:27,700 --> 00:23:33,100
Piec, szesc, siedem...

276
00:23:33,200 --> 00:23:36,800
osiem, dziewiec.

277
00:23:48,300 --> 00:23:52,600
The standard SS rate for Jewish skilled labor is seven marks a day,

278
00:23:52,600 --> 00:23:55,600
five for unskilled and women.

279
00:23:55,700 --> 00:23:58,700
This is what you pay the Reich Economic Office.

280
00:23:58,800 --> 00:24:01,300
the Jews themselves receive nothing.

281
00:24:01,400 --> 00:24:05,800
Poles you pay wages. Generally, they get a little more.

282
00:24:05,900 --> 00:24:08,500
Are you listening? What was that about the SS?

283
00:24:08,600 --> 00:24:10,800
The rate? The what?

284
00:24:10,900 --> 00:24:14,500
the Jewish worker's salary-- you pay it directly to the SS, not to the worker.

285
00:24:14,600 --> 00:24:16,700
He gets nothing. But it's less.

286
00:24:16,700 --> 00:24:18,800
It's less than what I would pay a Pole. It's less.

287
00:24:18,900 --> 00:24:21,800
That's the point I'm trying to make.

288
00:24:21,900 --> 00:24:24,500
Poles cost more.

289
00:24:24,600 --> 00:24:29,200
Why should I hire Poles?

290
00:24:29,300 --> 00:24:33,200
An enamelware factory over at, uh, Lipowa Street.

291
00:24:33,300 --> 00:24:36,200
It, uh, it, um-- It's owned by a German.

292
00:24:36,300 --> 00:24:39,400
But it's outside the ghetto, so you can barter for extra goods--

293
00:24:39,400 --> 00:24:41,700
for eggs, I don't know what you need--

294
00:24:41,800 --> 00:24:43,900
with the Polish workers. You can't get it here.

295
00:24:43,900 --> 00:24:48,200
Also, he's asking for ten healthy women for the-- I am healthy.

296
00:24:48,300 --> 00:24:51,300
Bring your sister, okay?

297
00:24:51,400 --> 00:24:55,500
[ Shouting Orders In German And Polish ]

298
00:24:55,600 --> 00:24:58,000
Chodz.

299
00:24:58,100 --> 00:25:01,500
You need to convince them you have a trade, something valuable to the war effort.

300
00:25:01,600 --> 00:25:03,800
Like what? What if you don't? I'm a musician.

301
00:25:03,900 --> 00:25:07,500
Your name goes on a list. And they put you on trucks--

302
00:25:07,600 --> 00:25:09,700
No, no, no, that's not true. You're a musician?

303
00:25:09,800 --> 00:25:12,300
Yeah. I'd find a good hiding place if I were you.

304
00:25:12,400 --> 00:25:16,900
I'm not going to hide like some animal. There are places to hide.

305
00:25:21,500 --> 00:25:23,400
Der Naechste!

306
00:25:23,500 --> 00:25:26,900
I'm a graduate of the University of Lwow.

307
00:25:26,900 --> 00:25:30,200
I used to work at the hydroelectric station in Roznow--

308
00:25:30,300 --> 00:25:32,200
Blauschein.

309
00:25:35,500 --> 00:25:39,400
I'm gonna get the necessary papers because this card is no good anymore.

310
00:25:39,500 --> 00:25:41,900
You can stay in this line all day, you'll still get one of these.

311
00:25:42,000 --> 00:25:45,700
They are no good. You'll have to leave the line now,

312
00:25:45,800 --> 00:25:50,400
then you'll get a blue card, a Blauschein, to say that you are an essential worker.

313
00:25:50,500 --> 00:25:53,600
I'll get these papers for you at Pankiewicz.

314
00:25:53,600 --> 00:25:55,600
Pharmacist. Just there, look.

315
00:25:55,700 --> 00:25:57,600
Guess who is here?

316
00:25:57,700 --> 00:26:00,400
Poldek! Enjoying the weather, Poldek?

317
00:26:00,500 --> 00:26:03,500
Enjoying the lines? Need some shoe polish?

318
00:26:03,500 --> 00:26:06,100
In a metal container maybe?

319
00:26:06,100 --> 00:26:10,600
Not essential? I think you misunderstand the meaning of the word.

320
00:26:10,700 --> 00:26:13,600
No Blauschein, sir. Stand over there.

321
00:26:13,700 --> 00:26:16,500
Move. Next!

322
00:26:16,600 --> 00:26:18,800
What do you mean, ''Not essential''?

323
00:26:18,900 --> 00:26:24,600
I teach history and literature. Since when is not essential?

324
00:26:29,900 --> 00:26:32,300
He's a metal polisher.

325
00:26:39,200 --> 00:26:42,000
It was not right? It's very good. He's 53 years old.

326
00:26:42,100 --> 00:26:45,200
It's too new. Mmm. Thank you.

327
00:26:53,400 --> 00:26:55,900
You're crazy. You left it in your drawer.

328
00:26:55,900 --> 00:26:58,200
How many times have I told you?

329
00:26:58,300 --> 00:27:01,000
Your work certificate you keep in your pocket at all times.

330
00:27:01,100 --> 00:27:03,000
And you leave everything in your drawer.

331
00:27:03,100 --> 00:27:05,500
How many times I've told you?

332
00:27:05,600 --> 00:27:08,800
I'm a metal polisher.

333
00:27:17,600 --> 00:27:20,200
Take the round sheet of tin,

334
00:27:20,300 --> 00:27:24,200
dip it in soap emulsion.

335
00:27:24,300 --> 00:27:29,400
Then place it centrally in the press.

336
00:27:44,600 --> 00:27:48,000
We obtain the soup pot. The soup pot.

337
00:27:48,100 --> 00:27:51,500
Soup pot.

338
00:27:51,600 --> 00:27:54,700
Grosz, Mrs. Grosz, stay together.

339
00:27:59,000 --> 00:28:04,200
Sir, I have ten work permits here for the Deutsche Emailwarenfabrik,

340
00:28:04,200 --> 00:28:07,100
cosigned by Mr. Bankier and myself.

341
00:28:07,100 --> 00:28:11,800
If it's carbonized, clean it with a file.

342
00:28:11,900 --> 00:28:16,700
But don't touch both the electrodes at the same time.

343
00:28:16,700 --> 00:28:19,900
You'll get electrocuted. Here, have a try.

344
00:28:24,300 --> 00:28:26,700
Roll the metal under the press,

345
00:28:26,800 --> 00:28:29,200
but be very careful unless you want your fingers...

346
00:28:29,300 --> 00:28:32,100
to become part of the teapot.

347
00:28:33,700 --> 00:28:37,400
Occupation? I'm a writer. I play the flute.

348
00:28:37,400 --> 00:28:40,900
But Moses is a skilled metalworker.

349
00:28:40,900 --> 00:28:43,200
He can make tin pots. He can make tanks.

350
00:28:43,300 --> 00:28:45,200
He can make whatever Mr. Schindler asks.

351
00:28:45,300 --> 00:28:47,900
He's highly skilled. Give him your card.

352
00:28:47,900 --> 00:28:50,300
Moses, give him your card.

353
00:28:52,400 --> 00:28:54,700
Now, dip the basin with the tongs...

354
00:28:54,800 --> 00:28:57,300
into the enamel solution.

355
00:28:59,400 --> 00:29:03,800
And after swiveling it around, carefully place it aside to drip dry.

356
00:29:06,800 --> 00:29:10,300
And whatever he asks you, allow me just to represent you and speak for you.

357
00:29:10,400 --> 00:29:12,400
Don't say a word.

358
00:29:12,500 --> 00:29:16,000
Filing, billing, keeping track of my appointments, shorthand.

359
00:29:16,000 --> 00:29:20,300
Typing, obviously. How is your typing? Uh, all right.

360
00:29:20,400 --> 00:29:22,300
Please.

361
00:29:38,500 --> 00:29:42,000
[ Typing Slowly, Bell Rings ]

362
00:29:47,600 --> 00:29:51,100
[ Typing Extremely Slow ]

363
00:30:15,200 --> 00:30:18,900
You need a secretary. Pick one.

364
00:30:18,900 --> 00:30:23,900
I don't know how. They're all so... qualified.

365
00:30:23,900 --> 00:30:26,900
You have to choose.

366
00:30:29,200 --> 00:30:32,000
Prosze sie ladnie usmiechac. Big smile. Big smile.

367
00:30:32,000 --> 00:30:33,500
Uwaga.

368
00:30:37,700 --> 00:30:39,900
####

369
00:30:53,000 --> 00:30:55,900
If you would, look after my guest.

370
00:30:56,000 --> 00:31:01,300
Um, boxed teas are good. Coffiee, pate, um...

371
00:31:01,300 --> 00:31:05,500
kielbasa sausage, cheeses, Beluga caviar. Yes.

372
00:31:05,600 --> 00:31:07,400
And, of course, who could live without German cigarettes?

373
00:31:07,500 --> 00:31:09,700
Get me as many as you can find.

374
00:31:09,800 --> 00:31:11,900
And some more fresh fruit.

375
00:31:12,000 --> 00:31:14,800
The real rarities-- oranges, lemons, pineapples.

376
00:31:14,800 --> 00:31:17,600
I need several boxes of Cuban cigars. The best. Yes.

377
00:31:17,600 --> 00:31:21,400
And dark, unsweetened chocolate. Not in the shape ofladyfigers, the chunk chocolate.

378
00:31:21,500 --> 00:31:24,600
Yes. Big as my hand, you sample at wine tastings.

379
00:31:24,700 --> 00:31:27,900
We're going to need lots of cognac. The best, Hennessy.

380
00:31:28,000 --> 00:31:33,400
Dom Perignon champagne. Um, get L 'espadon sardines...

381
00:31:33,500 --> 00:31:36,500
and, oh, try to find nylon stockings.

382
00:31:39,000 --> 00:31:42,200
It is my distinct pleasure to announce...

383
00:31:42,300 --> 00:31:47,900
the fully operational status of Deutsche Email Fabrik...

384
00:31:48,000 --> 00:31:49,300
Patrzjakies szmaty!

385
00:31:49,300 --> 00:31:52,800
manufacturers of superior enamelware crockery...

386
00:31:52,800 --> 00:31:58,300
expressly designed and crafted for military use.

387
00:31:58,300 --> 00:32:01,000
Utilizing only the most modern equipment,

388
00:32:01,100 --> 00:32:06,200
D.E.F. 's staffi of highly-skilled and experienced artisans and journeymen...

389
00:32:06,200 --> 00:32:09,800
deliver a product of unparalleled quality,

390
00:32:09,900 --> 00:32:13,800
enabling me to proffier, with absolute con ence and pride,

391
00:32:13,900 --> 00:32:16,500
a full line of field and kitchenware...

392
00:32:16,600 --> 00:32:20,700
unsurpassable in all respects by my competitors.

393
00:32:20,800 --> 00:32:23,400
See attached list and available colors.

394
00:32:23,500 --> 00:32:28,300
Anticipating the enclosed bids will meet with your approval.

395
00:32:28,400 --> 00:32:32,200
Made in Havana, Cuba. Looking forward to a long and mutually prosperous association.

396
00:32:32,300 --> 00:32:35,500
Look at this. I extend to you in advance my sincerest gratitude...

397
00:32:35,600 --> 00:32:38,500
and very best regards. Oskar Schindler.

398
00:32:38,600 --> 00:32:42,000
Yeah, I need 700 gross from here for next Thursday.

399
00:32:42,100 --> 00:32:44,900
Nine hundred-- No, make it ten for Wednesday.

400
00:32:44,900 --> 00:32:48,800
All this stuff here goes to Madritsch's factory on Tuesday of next week.

401
00:33:04,600 --> 00:33:08,000
My father was fond of saying, ''You need three things in life

402
00:33:08,100 --> 00:33:12,200
''a good doctor, a forgiving priest...

403
00:33:12,300 --> 00:33:15,500
and a clever accountant. ''

404
00:33:18,900 --> 00:33:23,000
The first two... I've never had much use for.

405
00:33:23,100 --> 00:33:26,500
But the third--

406
00:33:31,800 --> 00:33:35,300
Just pretend, for Christ's sake.

407
00:33:39,000 --> 00:33:42,200
Is that all?

408
00:33:47,000 --> 00:33:50,200
I'm trying to thank you.

409
00:33:50,300 --> 00:33:54,500
I'm saying I couldn't have done this without you.

410
00:33:57,000 --> 00:33:59,900
The usual thing would be to acknowledge my gratitude.

411
00:34:00,000 --> 00:34:04,900
It would also, by the way, be the courteous thing.

412
00:34:04,900 --> 00:34:07,800
You're welcome.

413
00:34:16,700 --> 00:34:18,900
Get out of here.

414
00:34:32,300 --> 00:34:35,500
Klonowska, who is it?

415
00:34:44,800 --> 00:34:47,500
She's so embarrassed. Look at her.

416
00:34:59,500 --> 00:35:01,800
You know something? You would like her.

417
00:35:01,900 --> 00:35:03,800
Oskar, please. What?

418
00:35:03,900 --> 00:35:06,300
I don't have to like her... just because you do. You would, though.

419
00:35:06,400 --> 00:35:09,200
It doesn't work that way.

420
00:35:21,900 --> 00:35:24,800
You've done well here.

421
00:35:27,200 --> 00:35:29,800
You look wonderful.

422
00:35:32,700 --> 00:35:36,200
Be careful of the step, miss. Mrs. Schindler, Marek.

423
00:35:43,000 --> 00:35:48,800
##

424
00:35:48,900 --> 00:35:52,900
It's not a charade, all this? How could it be a charade?

425
00:35:52,900 --> 00:35:55,400
The clothes, the car, the apartment. Wait a minute.

426
00:35:55,400 --> 00:35:59,400
Take a guess how many people are on my payroll. Oskar.

427
00:35:59,400 --> 00:36:05,200
My father, at the height of his success, had 50. I've got 3 50.

428
00:36:05,200 --> 00:36:09,500
3 50 workers on the factory floor, with one purpose.

429
00:36:09,600 --> 00:36:11,800
To make pots and pans?

430
00:36:11,900 --> 00:36:15,900
To make money. For me.

431
00:36:21,600 --> 00:36:24,800
Does anyone ask about me?

432
00:36:26,300 --> 00:36:29,500
Back home? Everybody.

433
00:36:29,600 --> 00:36:32,500
All the time.

434
00:36:32,600 --> 00:36:35,900
Hmm.

435
00:36:35,900 --> 00:36:41,500
They won't soon forget the name Schindler here, I can tell you that.

436
00:36:43,000 --> 00:36:46,200
''Oskar Schindler,'' they'll say.

437
00:36:46,300 --> 00:36:49,700
''Everybody remembers him.

438
00:36:49,800 --> 00:36:54,200
''He did something extraordinary.

439
00:36:54,300 --> 00:36:59,400
''He did something no one else did.

440
00:36:59,500 --> 00:37:02,800
''He came here with nothing--

441
00:37:02,900 --> 00:37:05,800
''a suitcase--

442
00:37:05,900 --> 00:37:11,500
''and built a bankrupt company into a major manufactory.

443
00:37:11,500 --> 00:37:15,100
''And left with a steamer trunk--

444
00:37:15,200 --> 00:37:19,800
''Two steamer trunks full of money,

445
00:37:19,900 --> 00:37:24,200
all the riches of the world.''

446
00:37:24,200 --> 00:37:26,200
Hmm.

447
00:37:26,200 --> 00:37:29,500
It's comforting to see that nothing's changed.

448
00:37:29,600 --> 00:37:33,200
You're wrong, Emilie.

449
00:37:33,200 --> 00:37:35,700
There's no way I could have known this before,

450
00:37:35,700 --> 00:37:39,200
but there was always something missing.

451
00:37:39,200 --> 00:37:43,300
In every business I tried, I can see now, it wasn't me that failed.

452
00:37:43,400 --> 00:37:46,200
Something was missing.

453
00:37:46,200 --> 00:37:49,800
Even if I'd known what it was, there's nothing I could have done about it...

454
00:37:49,900 --> 00:37:54,500
because you can't create this thing.

455
00:37:54,600 --> 00:37:59,900
And it makes all the difference in the world between success and failure.

456
00:37:59,900 --> 00:38:02,500
Luck?

457
00:38:04,900 --> 00:38:07,800
War.

458
00:38:31,300 --> 00:38:35,000
Should I stay?

459
00:38:35,100 --> 00:38:39,900
It's a beautiful city.

460
00:38:39,900 --> 00:38:44,900
I asked you if I should stay.

461
00:38:44,900 --> 00:38:48,000
It's up to you.

462
00:38:51,900 --> 00:38:56,500
Promise me, Oskar, no doorman or maitre d' will ever presume...

463
00:38:56,600 --> 00:39:02,000
I'm anyone other than Mrs. Schindler, and I'll stay.

464
00:39:04,200 --> 00:39:06,500
Good-bye, darling.

465
00:39:23,100 --> 00:39:27,300
I could try to read this or I could eat my lunch while it's still hot.

466
00:39:27,400 --> 00:39:29,400
We're doing well?

467
00:39:29,500 --> 00:39:30,700
Yes. Better this month than last?

468
00:39:30,800 --> 00:39:33,100
Yes. Any reason to think next month will be worse?

469
00:39:33,100 --> 00:39:36,400
The war could end.

470
00:39:46,300 --> 00:39:48,900
What? There is a machinist outside...

471
00:39:48,900 --> 00:39:52,000
who'd like to thank you personally for giving him a job.

472
00:39:52,100 --> 00:39:56,800
Every day he comes. He's very grateful. It'll just take a minute.

473
00:40:03,100 --> 00:40:05,500
Mr. Lowenstein?

474
00:40:12,500 --> 00:40:15,600
I want to thank you, sir,

475
00:40:15,600 --> 00:40:18,400
for giving me the opportunity to work.

476
00:40:18,500 --> 00:40:21,400
You're welcome. I'm sure you're doing a great job.

477
00:40:21,500 --> 00:40:25,800
The SS beat me up. They would have killed me,

478
00:40:25,900 --> 00:40:30,600
but I am essential to the war effort, thanks to you.

479
00:40:30,600 --> 00:40:32,600
That's great.

480
00:40:32,600 --> 00:40:35,300
I work hard for you.

481
00:40:35,300 --> 00:40:39,400
I'm sure you do. I'll continue to work hard for you.

482
00:40:39,500 --> 00:40:41,400
That's great. Thanks.

483
00:40:41,500 --> 00:40:44,000
God bless you, sir. All right.

484
00:40:44,000 --> 00:40:47,800
You are a good man.

485
00:40:49,200 --> 00:40:52,300
He saved my life. Yes, he did.

486
00:40:52,300 --> 00:40:55,200
God bless him. Yeah. Come on.

487
00:40:57,200 --> 00:41:00,100
God bless you.

488
00:41:12,100 --> 00:41:15,000
I'm sorry, Herr Direktor, but you're running very late.

489
00:41:15,100 --> 00:41:18,400
This is for the Obersturmbannfuehrer, sir.

490
00:41:18,400 --> 00:41:21,400
And this is for his niece, Greta. It's her birthday.

491
00:41:21,400 --> 00:41:24,200
Greta as in Garbo. By the way, don't ever do that to me again.

492
00:41:24,300 --> 00:41:26,900
Go. Go, go, drive! Don't bow.

493
00:41:26,900 --> 00:41:30,900
Did you happen to notice that that man had one arm? What? Did he?

494
00:41:34,600 --> 00:41:37,200
What's his use? Very useful.

495
00:41:39,900 --> 00:41:43,600
How? Very useful! Success!

496
00:41:51,300 --> 00:41:56,200
